    <p class="text-lg text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-6">British Columbia, particularly the Fraser Valley and Abbotsford, is renowned as Canada’s “Berry Capital.” With rich soil, mild climate, and a community of passionate farmers, the region produces some of the highest quality strawberries, blueberries, raspberries, and blackberries in the country. For many growers, berry farming is more than a business—it is a way of life, combining traditional agricultural knowledge with modern innovation.</p>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-800 leading-relaxed mb-10">However, producing high-quality berries is only half the challenge. Ensuring that these delicate fruits reach consumers in perfect condition requires careful attention to every step in the supply chain. From the moment berries are harvested to their arrival at farmers’ markets, grocery stores, or restaurants, packaging plays a pivotal role in protecting quality, reducing waste, and enhancing the overall customer experience.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Why Packaging Matters for Berry Farmers</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">Berry packaging does more than simply hold fruit. It serves multiple purposes that directly impact a farm’s profitability and reputation.</p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-8">
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Protection</span>: Berries are soft and fragile, making them prone to bruising and crushing. Packaging that provides cushioning and structure ensures that berries maintain their appearance and taste.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Shelf-life Extension</span>: Proper packaging, including ventilation and moisture control, helps berries stay fresh longer, giving farmers and retailers more flexibility in selling their products.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Efficiency in Handling</span>: Stackable trays and bins save space during storage and transport, making handling easier for farm laborers and distribution partners.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Visual Appeal</span>: The packaging that reaches the retail shelf communicates professionalism and quality to consumers. Bright, clean trays can elevate the perceived value of the product.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-10">In the competitive BC berry market, packaging is often the difference between a consumer choosing one farm’s produce over another. It is an investment that pays off in reduced losses, happier customers, and improved sales.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Understanding Berry Types and Their Packaging Needs</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-10">
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Strawberries</span>: Highly delicate, prone to bruising. They require trays that allow minimal movement and some level of separation between berries.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Blueberries</span>: Small but susceptible to crushing and moisture accumulation. Bulk trays with gentle ventilation help preserve their quality.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Raspberries</span>: Soft and easily crushed, divided trays that separate individual berries are ideal.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Blackberries</span>: Larger and slightly firmer, yet they still benefit from structured trays with proper airflow to prevent spoilage.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Mini Berry Trays</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">Mini berry trays are perfect for retail-ready servings or small portion packaging. Their compact size reduces movement during handling and transport, while stackability maximizes space efficiency. Farmers in Abbotsford have found that mini trays also enhance the visual appeal of their products on store shelves, encouraging consumers to purchase smaller, fresher portions.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Non-Divided Berry Trays</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">Non-divided trays accommodate larger quantities of berries like blueberries or bulk strawberries. These trays provide structural integrity and gentle containment, allowing airflow around the berries while keeping them safe from crushing during transport.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Divided Berry Trays</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-10">Divided trays are designed for premium presentation, separating each berry or small cluster to prevent bruising. They are especially useful for specialty markets, gift packaging, or farm-to-table sales, where appearance and freshness are paramount.</p>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-100 rounded-lg p-6 mb-10">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">Case Study: Abbotsford Strawberry Farm</h3>
      <p class="text-green-900/90 mb-4">One mid-sized strawberry farm in Abbotsford experienced significant losses—about 15–20% of harvested berries—due to inadequate packaging. Bruising during handling and transport led to spoilage before reaching local markets.</p>
      <p class="text-green-900/90 mb-4">After adopting a combination of mini and divided berry trays with proper ventilation from PACI NJ, the farm experienced remarkable improvements:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-green-900/90">
        <li><span class="font-semibold">Reduction in Losses</span>: Spoilage dropped to under 5%, directly increasing the farm’s revenue.</li>
        <li><span class="font-semibold">Enhanced Customer Satisfaction</span>: Retailers reported receiving fresher, more visually appealing berries.</li>
        <li><span class="font-semibold">Operational Efficiency</span>: Laborers found filling, stacking, and transporting berries easier due to ergonomic tray design.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Design Considerations for BC Berry Farmers</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-10">
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Ease of Handling</span>: Trays should be easy to fill and stack, reducing labor strain and time spent during harvest.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Visual Impact</span>: Bright, clean trays showcase the berries, making them more appealing to consumers.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Sustainability</span>: Reusable or recyclable trays align with the increasing consumer demand for eco-friendly products.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Ventilation</span>: Proper airflow prevents moisture buildup, which can cause mold or accelerate spoilage.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Color Coding and Sorting</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">Many farms benefit from color-coded trays to organize berries by type, ripeness, or quality grade. For example, using red trays for strawberries and green trays for blueberries helps farm staff quickly identify and sort fruit, minimizing errors and improving efficiency.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Stackability and Storage</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-8">Trays must be designed to be stackable without crushing the fruit below. Stackable designs save space during storage and transport, making it easier to move large quantities of berries from field to processing areas or delivery vehicles.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Sustainability in Packaging</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-10">Sustainability is more than a trend—it is a responsibility. Durable, reusable trays help reduce plastic waste, and recyclable materials support environmental initiatives. Light-colored trays, such as tan or white, can also reduce heat absorption during transport, preserving berry freshness.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Challenges BC Farmers Face</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-10">
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Climate and Humidity</span>: Berries are highly sensitive to temperature and moisture. Packaging must protect against heat, condensation, and sudden temperature changes during transit.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Transportation Logistics</span>: Whether transporting berries within the Fraser Valley or to Vancouver and beyond, proper packaging is crucial to prevent damage during handling, loading, and unloading.</li>
      <li><span class="font-semibold">Labor and Handling</span>: Multiple touchpoints during sorting, packing, and shipping increase the risk of bruising if trays are poorly designed or handled incorrectly.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Tips for Optimizing Berry Packaging</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-10">
      <li>Match trays to berry type: Different berries require different tray designs for optimal protection.</li>
      <li>Consider transport distances: Longer trips demand sturdier trays with better ventilation.</li>
      <li>Prioritize stackability: Save space while minimizing pressure on delicate berries.</li>
      <li>Incorporate color coding: Improves sorting efficiency and reduces handling mistakes.</li>
      <li>Focus on sustainability: Reusable or recyclable trays reduce waste and align with consumer preferences.</li>
      <li>Test packaging during harvest: Trial runs can identify potential issues before full-scale use.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Why PACI NJ Stands Out</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-10">
